h3. Issue Summary
A servlet in our product Vivid Trace for Jira is used to redirect the browser agent to various URLs. In the case where the browser is to receive a URI using the {{mailto:}} schema, Jira's code at {{RedirectInterceptingResponse.isPathInCurrentContext()}} causes a {{NullPointerException}}. The NPE arises because the code erroneously assumes a non-null value at an intermediate method invocation in both method calling chains, described below.

It would be great if the fix makes it into all future Jira releases. (Kindly see suggested fix below).

h3. Steps to Reproduce
Code sample to reproduce the bug:
{code:java}
public class RedirectionServlet extends HttpServlet {

    @Override
    protected void doGet(
            final HttpServletRequest request,
                         final HttpServletResponse response
    ) throws ServletException, IOException {
        response.sendRedirect("mailto:blinky-bill@outback.au");
    }

}
{code}

h3. Expected Results
Browser agent receives the redirect to the mailto: URI

h3. Actual Results
Throws an NPE
{noformat}
java.lang.NullPointerException
	at com.atlassian.web.servlet.plugin.request.RedirectInterceptingResponse.isPathInCurrentContext(RedirectInterceptingResponse.java:73) [?:?]
	at java.util.Optional.filter(Optional.java:178) [?:1.8.0_152]
	at com.atlassian.web.servlet.plugin.request.RedirectInterceptingResponse.locationWithinCurrentContext(RedirectInterceptingResponse.java:64) [?:?]
	at com.atlassian.web.servlet.plugin.request.RedirectInterceptingResponse.forward(RedirectInterceptingResponse.java:48) [?:?]
	at com.atlassian.web.servlet.plugin.request.RedirectInterceptingResponse.sendRedirect(RedirectInterceptingResponse.java:36) [?:?]
	at javax.servlet.http.HttpServletResponseWrapper.sendRedirect(HttpServletResponseWrapper.java:138) [servlet-api.jar:?]
	at com.atlassian.core.filters.HeaderSanitisingResponseWrapper.sendRedirect(HeaderSanitisingResponseWrapper.java:85) [atlassian-core-5.0.9.jar:?]
	at vivid.trace.servlets.RedirectionServlet.doGet(RedirectionServlet.java:40) [?:?]
	at javax.servlet.http.HttpServlet.service(HttpServlet.java:635) [servlet-api.jar:?]
	[ ... remainder elided ... ]
{noformat}

h3. Notes
* Bug not present in at least Jira version 6.3.13
* Bug is expressed on at least Jira versions 7.13.1, 8.0.2

h3. Suggested fix
Current Jira code that causes the NPE:
{code:java}
    private boolean isPathInCurrentContext(URI location) {
        final String contextPath = request.getContextPath();
        return location.getRawPath().startsWith(contextPath) || !location.getRawPath().startsWith("/");
    }
{code}

Suggested fix:
{code:java}
    private boolean isPathInCurrentContext(URI location) {
        final String contextPath = request.getContextPath();
        final String rawPath = location.getRawPath();
        // NOTE: rawPath could be null.
        return rawPath != null && (rawPath.startsWith(contextPath) || !rawPath.startsWith("/"));
    }
{code}

h3. Workaround
Currently, there is no known workaround for this behavior, however, a suggested fix is in place.

h3. Issue Summary
When editing an active workflow, a draft will be created with the modifications and only make those effective once the draft is published. However, if you deactivate a workflow (remove it from all schemes), the draft is discarded regardless of having changes.

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Edit an active workflow (assigned to at least one workflow scheme;
# Apply any modification to it;
# Go back to the "Workflows" screen and navigate to the scheme/s associated with that workflow, and disassociate it from it/them;
# Notice that the workflow will be moved to the "Inactive" section and its draft, discarded;

h3. Expected Results
The draft should be kept with the applied changes.

h3. Actual Results
Changes are lost upon deactivating the workflow.

h3. Workaround
Make sure changes are published to the workflow prior to making it inactive.

h3. Issue Summary
When deleting a user with @ in username, if this user still assigned with some JIRA tickets, JIRA will redirect us to a JQL query to remove this user from assignee. The JQL query showing below auto generated JQL query with errors.
{code}
assignee in (dan@dan) ORDER BY priority ASC
{code}
{code}
Error in the JQL Query: The character '@' is a reserved JQL character. You must enclose it in a string or use the escape '\u0040' instead. (line 1, character 17)
{code}
(i) This is expected behavior as "@" was a reserved character. Manually add "" to user name could fix it, but JIRA auto generated JQL query should also cater this secneario.

h3. Environment
JIRA 7.6.9, JIRA 8.0.1

h3. Steps to Reproduce
# Create a user with username contain *@* symbol
# Assign this user as assignee for some tickets
# Try to delete user from user management directory
# JIRA will prompt:-
{code}
Cannot delete user. 'dan@dan' has associations in JIRA that cannot be removed automatically.
Change the following and try again:
Assigned Issue: 1 issue
{code}
# Click on "*Assigned Issue: 1 issue*" you will be redirected to a JQL search

h3. Expected Results
JQL using below code to search:-
{code}
assignee in ("test@test") ORDER BY priority ASC
{code}

h3. Actual Results
JIRA using below JQL and showing error below:-
{code}
assignee in (dan@dan) ORDER BY priority ASC
{code}
{code}
Error in the JQL Query: The character '@' is a reserved JQL character. You must enclose it in a string or use the escape '\u0040' instead. (line 1, character 17)
{code}

h3. Workaround
Manually include *"* before and after username

{panel:bgColor=#e7f4fa}
*NOTE:* This suggestion is for *JIRA Server*. Using *JIRA Cloud*? [See the corresponding suggestion|http://jira.atlassian.com/browse/JRACLOUD-45727].
{panel}
The *Download Jira Software Server* page is not clear on what is the latest version available for download. Indicating which version is available will help customers decide whether they want to click _Download_ or change to _All Server versions._

